Great selection of clothes at reasonable prices.  There are even designer labels. Nice shoe and purse selection as well.  Seems like they downsized the home decor and domestics selection. Only negative was at checkout where the cashier decided to lecture me on the divinity I was buying for my husband.  She informed me the first ingredient was sugar, to which I answered, yes that's what divinity is made from.  She then asked if I was trying to giveu husband diabetes.  Wow.< /review>

<Text>Many KUDOs for the service provided over the past week from Jonathan Garcia.  I had an ageing American Standard toilet that had been problematic the past few years.  I had an on-going intermittent "ghosting" for several years that was infrequent enough that I just ignored it.  More recently, I was getting drips that turned out to be from a loose bolt connecting the tank to the bowl, and a dampness on the floor around the toilet.  After Jonathan's first visit he quickly found the loose bolt and tightened it and replaced the gasket in the tank with one that I provided.  Unfortunately, (and I was warned) it might not work since it wasn't an American Standard gasket.  After a few hours my ghosting was much more severe but Jonathan had showed me what he did so I ordered and replaced the gasket myself.  In the meantime, I had panicked and call Allbritten to have Jonathan return for the next available appointment a few days later.  I was still getting water from someplace that needed to be diagnosed.  When he returned, Jonathan replaced the wax ring and inspected the toilet.  Unfortunately (I just can't catch a break), he found a crack in my bowl.  After some discussion, I ordered a Toto toilet which I hadn't heard of before.  The next day he returned and installed the new Toto.  I have to say that the new Toto is so much better than the American Standard I had. < Text>
I had been using Allbritten for years.  My high expection for their high quality service and reasonable value came to an end.

The technician came for the maintenance service.  He found out that the defrost control board needed to be replaced.  He quoted us $352 (discount included!).  I questioned about the necessity of the service, but I agreed with the quote anyway.  He came back to complete the service, and he found another issue with the thermostat.  He quoted me $295 for the replacement.  I felt it would be an unreasonable price, but I agreed anyway.  I found out later that the non-programable thermostat only costs me $35.  How did the $295 service cost justify an add-on service that only costs them $35 for the material and  less than 30 minutes of labor???

I called the following day to talk to the office manager.  She confirmed the service cost of $295.  She gave me $30 refund.  My expense went down to $265.  Does it make me feel like a valued customer? Nope!  I felt like I was robbed.  According to homeadvisor.com, " For a standard, 2,000-square-foot home, the cost of installing or replacing a thermostat averages between $112 and $252, including the price of the unit and professional installation. The national average cost is $173."  Allbritten charged me at least 1.5  to 2 times higher than the national average.  With out the 15% memership discount or $51 discount they offered me, my cost could go up to $346 ($295 + $51)!!!

I still give Allbritten 5 stars for the service.  I only give them 1 star for the value.  Unlike the 5 stars they received from me in the past, they only get 3 stars overall under my evaluation.< /Text>

The home Owner and I are very good friends and as a tenant I respect our landlord and do not want her to be overcharged especially on parts. 1557863657262<//time>
< resp>
{'time': 1557873592722, 'text': "We apologize but we don't compromise on our pricing. It's called an upfront, flat-rate price. The diagnostic fee of $65 is not to 'lock you in with us' but rather to help us partially cover some of our costs of labor, our truck costs to drive out to your home, our training to diagnose the problem, etc. You are never locked in with us. We are more than willing to diagnose the problem, tell you the cost of the repair up-front, and if you don't like the pricing of the repair, you're welcome to take our knowledge of what repair is needed and do business with someone else or repair it yourself! We don't do our pricing with an hourly rate, but rather as a flate-rate price for the repair, which is an advantage to you! You know the price ahead of time, no matter how long it takes us! You don't have to hold your breath, wondering if we are dragging the job out simply to charge more, and not every knowing the cost until AFTER we are done and you're STUCK with paying it. If we run into a snag, have to drive to the supply house, takes us longer than assumed, etc it's the same price to you! We hope this helps to explain. We hope you're able to get the repair done and have a comfortable and cool home again!\n\n~Andrea\nallbritten.com"}</resp>

<response>{'time': 1557873592722, 'text': "We apologize but we don't compromise on our pricing. It's called an upfront, flat-rate price. The diagnostic fee of $65 is not to 'lock you in with us' but rather to help us partially cover some of our costs of labor, our truck costs to drive out to your home, our training to diagnose the problem, etc. You are never locked in with us. We are more than willing to diagnose the problem, tell you the cost of the repair up-front, and if you don't like the pricing of the repair, you're welcome to take our knowledge of what repair is needed and do business with someone else or repair it yourself! We don't do our pricing with an hourly rate, but rather as a flate-rate price for the repair, which is an advantage to you! You know the price ahead of time, no matter how long it takes us! You don't have to hold your breath, wondering if we are dragging the job out simply to charge more, and not every knowing the cost until AFTER we are done and you're STUCK with paying it. If we run into a snag, have to drive to the supply house, takes us longer than assumed, etc it's the same price to you! We hope this helps to explain. We hope you're able to get the repair done and have a comfortable and cool home again!\n\n~Andrea\nallbritten.com"}< /response>< Pics>

Customer service is absolutely amazing from start to finish. I called into their office at 10:30 am to report my heater was not coming on, i was greeted by Mindy, who was friendly and understanding. She was able to get a service technician out the same day between 11-1 with a call to confirm when Mike S. was in his way. I got a call at 11 to say he'd be there in 15 minutes. Mike S. arrived with a business card in hand and had already read over the previous repairs before coming in. (Allbritten had been out a couple months prior to repair another situation we had with wiring.) Mike asked pertinent questions as he looked over our thermostat and then went into the basement to get started. He took photos on his phone to show me the problem and explained in in a matter I could understand. Mike then gave me the options to repair. I decided to go with his recommendation. He came inside, made some changes on my thermostat, because it wasn‚Äôt installed properly the first time, and then tested the AC and heater. This started out to be a really good experience. I had an issue with my water spigot outside of my kitchen. It was leaking and needed repair. The price was a little high at $380.00 for replacing it, but since they were out here on a Saturday, I went with it. Let me say, this has absolutely nothing to do with the service technician (James Sabourin). He did an excellent job, was fast and courteous, and did a good job. However, he noticed the yard hose spigot (on the same repair) was leaking and suggested changing it. I asked him if he had the part, he did, so I said "sure, change it." This is an $8.00 hose spigot every person reading this is familiar with when they water their yard with a hose. He was still in the middle of completing the other repair so it was no additional service call. Literally took him two minutes to put on. When it came time to pay, I got a bill for $510.00. I was flabbergasted. I asked him, "you mean to tell me that an $8.00 spigot that took you two minutes to put was $130.00?" I could understand if I had them return on another call, or he was finished and ready to leave and had to come back with his tools, but he was literally finishing what he was doing and added the spigot. I can purchase and change this myself (and will) in a manner of minutes. You talk about terrible customer service. James almost had me ready to order the yearly air conditioning service as well. My a/c fan and motor went out and we needed service.  We have a home warranty, but when we called them the first contractor they assigned to us, Martinez Mechanical, never bothered to contact us for the appointment (they're supposed to contact us within 24 hrs).  I tried to contact them and kept getting the "the mailbox you've reached is full....so I texted them, and they responded "who is this"? I explained that my home warranty referred me to them and never a response.  The next place assigned to me, Indoor Quality Services, contacted me right away, but could not schedule someone to come out until the following Tuesday (this was Thursday, in California heat of 97+ temp, with no a/c).  I decided to call Allbritten instead.  Although I had to pay much more than I would have had I gotten to use my home warranty, it was worth not having to smolder in the California heat for another week. < Text>
First of all: Albritten showed up on time, was professional and courteous, and repaired my AC unit. Thank you for that.
The down side:
This is the 3rd time i have used allbritten for AC repairs, twice on a rental home and this time on my residence. Our AC stopped cooling on Saturday and I called and chose to wait for them to come at their earliest appointment on Monday, preferring to use a company I have history with. On Monday, i had scheduled a $59 diagnostic appointment, and 2 servicemen showed up and in under 10minutes diagnosed my capacitor was dead. They stated they had the part on the truck and could replace it for about $275 plus the diagnostic fee. It was 107 yesterday and I had friends coming for dinner and in my own ignorance I said do it. Another 10-15 minutes later I have a working AC unit and a bill that I happily pay for a total of $333.00.
That night talking to several people who came over, 2 of them said they had had similar problems with their AC and the repair was significantly cheaper, so the next day I chose to call around to some of the local competitors, and received a average quote of around $150 for the repair including the parts.
I am at fault for not price checking and becoming to comfortable with a company. But I also will no longer be using Allbritten due to their hyper inflated pricing. I understand the $59 diagnostic fee, but to find out I was charged nearly double the going rate for a job that took 15min and replacing a part that costs $45 on amazon I feel taken advantage of. It's to bad, their servicepeople have all been very happy and professional, but at 2x the going rate for their work who wouldn't have a huge smile on their face all of the time?</Text>

< review>
Our home was recently invaded by a family of rats looking to create their own watering hole in the attic by chewing through the Aquapex water line. With Fresno in a 4-year drought these creatures were looking for water in any place that they could find it. The leak they created made its way through the ceiling in the kitchen and caused us to seek an immediate repair.

Our insurance company recommended Allbritten, The Barefoot Plumber, so I we called to schedule an appointment. Meagan, in their Customer Service Department could not have been more efficient in ensuring that we had the earliest available time for their  specialist to make the the call. When Aaron arrived the next morning we were greeted by a friendly, knowledgable, and efficient plumbing repair person. Aaron went right to work to locate the leak, cut and replace the chewed section of Aquapex and make a leak test to further ensure that the job was properly completed. He then went out of his way to give us some background on rat behavior so that we could relay it to our pest control service and hopefully avoid a repeat performance.

Would we recommend Allbritten to another person in need of a plumbing problem? Absolutely, and with the knowledge that the job would be done right, completed on time, and reasonably priced. Their customer service staff and repair service personnel made a good outcome out of a bad situation. Way to go Allbritten!<//review>

< Text>

She had Allbrittin to come and service her A\C unit. After signing a paper to allow the technician to tune up/check the AC. <Date>1464179381354<//Date><Rate>5</Rate>< review>
Allbritten is great. We needed to repipe our house. Our galvanized pipes were deteriorating and we had lead in some of our water. I interviewed four companies for the job. Repiping a house is a big job. I wanted to make sure we had it done right. Of the four companies interviewed, I chose Allbritten. I chose them because they had the best insights into repiping our house. I also chose them because they are a large company and I knew that, if anything should go wrong, they would take care of it. I also chose them because the plumber who came to talk to me about the job, Jimmy, was very professional, polite, and personable. We had a good rapport. He listened to my concerns and discussed solutions with me. I felt like he heard me and took my concerns seriously. He was knowledgeable about different technical details of plumbing which, I had found, other plumbers weren't aware. For instance, as I have learned, one should never join copper and galvanized directly together as the metals react and contribute to the deterioration of galvanized. Also, for instance, Jimmy pointed out that building standards are to use 95/5 solder when joining copper pipes and that there is *still* lead in 95/5 solder (5% of it is lead). His knowledge, and concern for my concerns, were great. When it came to doing the job, Allbritten's work was also great. Jimmy and his partner Dustin worked hard and intelligently. They cleaned up every day, leaving our house as undisturbed as possible. They were very polite. They were courteous. They did great work. All in all, our job proved to be much more involved than it appeared from the outset. Jimmy and Dustin had to put in several extra days of work, but Allbritten kept their word on their bid and didn't even bring up the issue or try to renegotiate. It is without hesitation that I recommend Allbritten. And if Jimmy is available, I recommend you request him. ONE LAST THING TO KNOW: the secretary at the company suggested I sign up for the "Guardianship Protection Program" which would cost about $250 and would (1) include the servicing of our air conditioners twice a year and (2) save us 15% on this very big job. Woohoo! Thank you, Allbritten, Jimmy, and Dustin!< /review>

<Gmap_id>0x80c297b7cbb1acf5:0x9bde7668df25b15f</Gmap_id><username>Cary Brown</username>< review>
A friendly, healthy Korean "rice bowl" style counter service restaurant. Servings are generous, suprisingly good and cooked to order. The delicious vegan bowl contains charbroiled tofu, crisp veggies, brown rice, and is lightly topped with teriyaki sauce. The bowl is also available with Kobe beef or skinless chicken breast meat. Fresh chives and avocado may be added. All proteins are charbroiled. Brown rice or polished (white) rice are interchangeable. Two hot sauces and a Teriyaki sweet sauce are offered. Wheelchair accessible including a gender neutral bathroom requiring a security code, which is printed on your cash register receipt. Easy, free wheelchair accessible parking in two lots. A short tunnel connects.< /review>

< Time>
1589565776283<//Time>
<rate>5</rate><review>Been going here nearly every weekday in the afternoon since late March 2019 due to strictly monitoring my caloric intake. Food is good and consistent; staff is nice, courteous, and professional. Water is filtered and cold, even without ice. Patrons here can sometimes be messy (like most places), but staff keeps things clean. I've been served by the owner a few times, who is kind and jovial.

As to what I order, I religiously order 1 chicken & veggie bowl with brown rice and no green onions. I top it with hot sauce, triple hot sauce, jalapenos, and black pepper. (Yes, I like it hot, even as tears start coming out out.) Staff knows me by sight now and knows what I'll be ordering.

I hate avocado, but they serve it here and people order it frequently enough so I guess it's good. I've also had the beef bowl, the half & half, and plate-size portions before. All are good; the orange slice and salad on the plate are simple but surprisingly refreshing, which is kinda' Flame Broiler in a nutshell.

This place is my peaceful little lunch getaway from work and generally the highlight of my work day. Parking in the plaza is pretty bad but I walk here for lunch anyway!

Protip: The restroom code is printed out on your receipt, but I'm assuming no one notices that. Staff will readily give the code to customers when asked anyway.<//review><pictures>None<//pictures>< resp>
None< /resp>

<Review>Not a place I would recommend for authentic Chinese food. The food is Chinese fusion. I think many people go to the restaurant because of Martin Yan's name.

The interior decor of the restaurant is unique. My favorite is the big antique bell at the bar. The seating, however, is very uncomfortable. The tables are placed too close to each other, with little room for people to walk through. The dishes look & sound creative, but the taste is really unimpressive.

For the price it charges, the customer service of this restaurant is disappointing! Most staff are courteous, but they don't know how to serve. When serving the soup, the usual Chinese etiquette is to pour the soup for all the guests at the table. But the server just put the soup and utensils on the table and left. Moreover, the Latino looking woman literally dropped the bowl of sauce in the middle of the table, and didn't even apologize for her rudeness.

Overall, the service and the food don't live up to M.Y. China's name.<//Review><gmap_id>0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1<//gmap_id>< UserId.>
103499601184173589405</UserId.>

< review>
Awesome spot!!! It is truly hard to go wrong with restaurants here in San Francisco. There are so many options to choose from, especially in this area and in the mall. Very pleased with the decision to follow the Chinese craving! This is a more upscale Chinese restaurant with a variety of rice, noodle, soup, meat dishes to choose from. We made the decision to eat here simply because of how good the food looked while walking by. Presentation of the dishes was very nice and the flavors were even better!! Service was average but the food made up for it. They have some of the best chicken wings I've ever had. Noodles were also delicious! If you are looking for a good meal while at the mall, I definitely recommend checking M.Y. China out!!</review>

< user_name>
Tina Tsong<//user_name>
<userid>110044408245887412132< /userid><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPLcwQWWkffY8M5aaR0lf5Wg4w5WUEFDSpbcPxW=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMenYUAf1utww78c7B8BTsDgbsAVX6Or6nmkaCi=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNdDaG5WgbSoRPLPCL54ZBg5eN9-ww5NXhLW-vu=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMIpuadHAGbbSlo6xHpq5UGshvZ44ticVo3NWLz=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMPJJ14C2YCW_fwFQ6a3g6WD7yKdUc9Ey067jwf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures><review>We waited briefly at noon on Sunday before we were seated. The dining area definitely started to get more packed while we were eating.
1) tea smoked pork belly sliders: good but there is no hint of tea flavor. The bao is soft and well steamed, but the pork belly is ordinary if not slightly bland.
2) Wild Boar Scissor Cut Noodles: the wild boar is diced into small indistinguishable pieces that it almost seemed like an afterthought in the dish. The noodles and sauce were unexpectedly commonplace in texture and flavor.
3) Dan Dan noodles: thin noodles are served cold in a peanut sauce. A lot of restaurants serve this differently, and this one is of the less notable versions.
4) Mushroom with spicy sesame sauce: the mushrooms have a great meaty texture, but one could not taste any sesame. The sauce instead bordered on the glossy sweet side.
5) eggplant and tofu clay pot: would definitely recommend for the soft tofu dredged in cornstarch and gently fried. The eggplant in the dish is cooked well
6) Yang zhou fried rice: delicious but very ordinary. Easily found and replicated by many restaurants.
7) Peking roast duck: the skin is crisp and well done. Also recommended.

M.Y. China is one of the better mall restaurants but certainly sits average among the category of americanized Cantonese food. While I will probably not return due to the conventional menu and flavors, I can definitely see it as a good alternative to the less exciting options at the mall.<//review><gmap_id>0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1< /gmap_id>< response>

<gmapID>0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1</gmapID>< review>
I cant say enough about how much I love this place. Everything is made fresh, including (and especially) the noodles. The soups are flavorful and delicious, the entrees are elegant. But one of my favorite things here is the spicy crispy tofu...I could eat that all day long! My China is on the 4th floor of the Westfield mall, so if you're having a hard time finding it, take the elevator to the 4th floor (under the dome). There is sometimes a wait, but it's usually only 10-20 mins and it's worth it!</review>

<name>Master Maggie Li<//name>< Response>

< gmapID>
0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1</gmapID>
<pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNVz020TDATP_kE_zzO9COej1D403YLmV-qlNg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOZWEgE6hzVXrnikry5jruqqsIH2_rlUTj83FM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPLKHsT4mbIIdiIMBwuxfRcmw6m4EOI0cGGB3U=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Review>
I always forget MY China when I choose where to eat in SF. But with the horrible air quality, we decided to stay inside Westfield Mall after getting off of BART. And I'm glad we did. Sadly we missed Happy Hour (Monday-Friday 3-6PM, mostly discounted alcoholic drinks).

I highly recommend the Da Dao "Big Knife" Seafood Noodle - stir-fried noodle with generous portion of seafood (scallop, squid, shrimp), shiitake mushroom (my fav), baby oyster mushroom, pea sprouts and stringy egg. Such good work flavor! It was good to eat with other saltier dish as it was a bit bland, so I asked for some chili sauce and that definitely elevated the dish. Must-try! Eggplant tofu clay pot had pieces of soft, lightly fried tofu with chunks of eggplant. It was a soy sauce-based dish, and had some basil for flavoring; a little oily though.

Overall, great American Chinese food! But of course it was more expensive than your usual Chinese restaurant. Also they make interesting cocktaiIs. If you are a drinker, try to make it to Happy Hour.</Review>

<Name>C Craig Barton<//Name><time>1505274583932</time><rate>2</rate>< Text>
I wouldn't go back.

First , service was super slow and did-engaged.  We sat and waited a lot and had to ask for help.  Took 20 minutes after we were seated to get our water and first drink.  And that was after asking for it twice.

Food is hit or miss.  But sweet and sour pork was super chewy.  My beef noodle soup, the beef was excellent, but the broth was meh'

Seating can be really really tight.  We pretty much had dinner with the people next to us.

For the price , and location, I would definitely recommend going somewhere else.<//Text>

< Text>
Mysterious vibes in the restaurant, the lighting is dark. Good for parties, friends meet ups. The  waiters were decent friendly. Noted here, the dandan noodles are served cold with sliced carrots on top which is different from originals and its not so meaty, but still worth a try. The crab dumpling was placed over a pice of veggie, server with a kind of red sweet/sour liquidish sauce, the dumplings were juicy as you would expected but fairy decent taste. Would recommend it if you wanna have dumplings once a while. Also connivence location, its located on the top floor of westfield. Right next to the elevator, easy to found. Different from the open fast restaurants on the F1, it is actually a well-decorated American Chinese restaurant.< /Text>

< review>
I've been here a couple of times and in general I like the food a lot. It's in a fun location, which might make it feel a bit commercial, but I enjoy coming here to eat.

The food itself is generally pretty good. Can't go wrong with the dumplings, my favorites being the pork juicy dumplings or the BBQ pork bao. You can always do yourself a favor and get the Dim Sum collection which gives you a sample of the dumplings.

The beef noodle soup is also a treat. The one item I had that I wasn't terribly impressed with was the honey walnut shrimp, which came out a bit cold. Either way, looking forward to my next visit already.</review>

< review>
I'm sorry it's in a mall and not down a picturesque alley in Chinatown, but it's simply better than almost any Chinese place in town. If you like fresh, high end, not too adventurous, but thorough tasty Chinese food. I say this not because the food is better than any number of places I could name, but because the overall experience makes this a civilized, clean experience, with a great bar, big pretty well appointed room, and a solid go-to place. (And p.s., my favorite Chinese place---well one of them is a Szechuan place out Clement Street, and it's absolutely filthy. Same with the other place I could name on Kearny in Chinatown, a gross disgusting mess with a waitress who always has on the same unlaundered seat shirt each time I go. Food is divine at both places, but honestly, I don't want to have to deal with those places most of the time.)</review>

I‚Äôve been there twice as it is across the street from my hotel. The positive stuff first. If you are a fan of Peking duck, they do it very well and it‚Äôs reasonably priced. One half portion is plenty for two people ($24). I‚Äôve also had the house fried rice which was good but not that special for $13 (a small portion) and any decent Chinese restaurant can do it the same and even better. Now the negative. Two extremely disappointing items were the dumpling sampler ($15 for 6) and the salt and pepper calamari. The dumplings were bland and absolutely tasteless - all 3 flavors were blech. The calamari was like eating a breaded car tire, thick breading and tough/chewy. They were equally wretched ... and I don‚Äôt get to use that word often. We were planning to order one of the Market priced lobster dishes, but at $60+ it wasn‚Äôt worth the risk when two very simple dishes were disappointments. As this seems to be a mid to higher end priced restaurant, I expected better quality for the price. I will say the wait staff is nice and somewhat attentive, but overall it was a thumbs down for us and I gave it two chances. Venture down Geary St for much better quality, variety AND value. Peking Duck and service makes it 3 stars for me.<//Text>

<user_id>107638344958166913760<//user_id>< text>
I was excited to try M.Y. China as it was a cold and rainy day in the city and I was really looking forward to some excellent Chinese cuisine. That said, I was really disappointed in M.Y. China. I was excited to see that many dishes could be made gluten-free and after learning that the Beef Noodle Soup could not be made gluten-free, the waiter suggested the Venison Chow Mein which I enthusiastically said yes to, having never tasted Venison. Unfortunately when the dish arrived, it came with about 5 pieces of Venison and a large amount of uninspiring noodles and bean sprouts. The Venison was good, but the rest of the dish was lackluster. I will say that the service was good; the house manager came over to make sure I had been greeted and given a menu and I was able to cool my heels there for over an hour without feeling pressured to leave. I just wish the food had been more exciting.<//text>

It was a challenge to order more dishes as the waiter, though good, was stretched thin as he was the only one authorized to submit an order. <user>115362898003952244191<//user>< user_name>
Elisa Lou</user_name>
<Date>1458626909020< /Date><rate>4</rate>< review>
Surprisingly good experience here. There can be a wait, so I recommend just reserving through OpenTable since they put priority on those with reservations (they allow same day).

If you are craving legitimate Chinese food after some shopping but are too lazy to make it to the Richmond or Chinatown, just go here!

We got the string beans, Peking duck (half), and beef noodle soup. The beef noodle soup was very good, I actually don't know where else to get this dish since sf is so lacking of authentic Taiwanese food. The Peking duck was great as well, though I wish they provided the thin pancake slices to eat with instead of the steamed buns. The string beans were pretty standard and nothing special.

The service was also really great - despite us having a seat more towards the outdoor area, our waitress Jessica was super attentive.

We are glad to have a good Peking duck option in sf, without having to trek to Berkeley.  I wouldn't mind coming back again.< /review>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
Mu Shu Pork Tacos are the best I‚Äôve ever had. I teared up when eating them because they are out of this world. I could eat them every day of my life for breakie, lunch and dinner and be utterly blown away by every bite. The noodles are a must!! The chef received an award for his noodles recently - they are magnificent. Beijing Knife Cut Noodles are so flavorful with the mushroom combination, a little kick of spice and delicious pork. Bring groups of friends, family or business here for a taste of China that  is unlike anything in San Francisco.</Text>

<Text>The food and service was pleasantly good, I ordered Brasied Tofu garnished with Jalape√±o, along with Jasmine Rice, Vegetable Spring Rolls and Spinach noodles soup with 5 types of mushrooms.
The food taste was the closest I have experienced since visiting Mainland China, the quality of the ingredients stood out the most. The Tofu was Crisp and a delight to eat, Spring rolls were extra hot and I loved them as they were not drenched in oil, the soup was a 8 out of 10 just because it was a veggie so it was missing the taste pork would typically add, understandably I had ordered a Vegan Soup!
The price was the real surprise the whole thing was $43.00 which included $11.00 in beverages alone. The service super quick and pleasant, really I‚Äôd like to give them 6 Stars. Highly Recommend this place.< /Text>< Pictures>

We visited this restaurant twice in one week.  On a weekday, the service was OK, but absolutely terrible on a Saturday night.  At first, we were told it was a 20 minute wait for a table, after 30 minutes of waiting we were told it would be another 15 minutes!  Then all of a sudden, we were able to be seated straight away. Once we were sat down it took about 15 minutes for someone to take our drink order and another 15 for us to actually get our drinks.  Food is great though and worth the wait.< /Review>

<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Gotta start off by saying that we were served by perhaps the best waitress I have ever experienced. She was spot on with timing, suggestions, encouragement, and just the right amount of humor. Type of server I imagine at a much more expensive place that this. Food was really good. We picked out a few items and then our server filled in the blanks to get an awesome family-style meal. Pork tacos and the king pao chicken really stuck out as did the walnut shrimp. Decor wasn't really inviting, but the food and service was so good, I barely noticed.</Review>

< Review>
This place is pricey but many of the quality of the food and the ambiance make it worth it for the most part. I went for lunch on a Friday. The shiu mai was delicious, but at $8 overpriced in my opinion. The Hong Kong crispy noodles were came with generous portions of chicken and bok choy. The noodles were crisp and the accompanying sauce was gooey but not overpowering. The wok seared beef had tender and delicious beef chunks, although the sauce was a bit too salty for my liking.</Review>

< review>
One waitress cheated on the tip! My bill was $30.65, the printed tip of 20% on the bill was $10.86 which was actually more than 35%.  I am always generous on tips so I just blindly paid that number.  I just realized this cheating trick after I was back home but I didn't keep my bill.
Double check all the numbers on the bill before you pay it and keep the bill.</review>

< text>
Wonderfully delicious dinner!  I ate here with a group of about 15 friends last night, sharing many dishes, and was surprised and delighted that I loved *everything*!  Great flavors, texture, meat quality, etc.  And very attentive service!  Our water glasses were refilled frequently, the table was wiped and cleared several times, and so on.

Also, the owner, Martin Yan, came by our table to say hi, sporting a big friendly grin.  You can tell he's truly in love with making people happy with food :).

My only quibble was that the seating was a bit uncomfortable (I was pretty squished up against the guy sitting at the table next to me) and a couple of us kept getting dripped on by a condensed pipe above our heads :\.  But this situation might have been due to us trying to squeeze way too many people into a single long table and likely doesn't reflect the normal seating situation.

I look forward to returning and trying more from the super-tasty and well-executed menu!< /text>

1458287419574</Date>
< rating>
1< /rating>
< text>
IF YOU HAVE FOOD ALLERGIES AVOID THIS PLACE!!!!!

TLDR: of the 2 dishes I ordered, they screwed up 4 times and would have given me a severe allergic reaction!

I went to My China on Wed evening with my CEO and several of his friends. I explained my food allergies of peppers, cayenne, chili powder and anything "spicy" to the waitress and was advised I could eat the fried chicken appetizer, rice and sweet and sour chicken.

The waitress brought the fried chicken wings and it was immediately obvious that it was covered in cayenne or chili powder with peppers on top of it. All of which I am very allergic to. The waitress apologized and promised that she would make sure it didn't happen again.

She brought out the order and promised it was fine as she had personally talked to the head chef and he was extra careful. I almost took a bite when my dining companions told me to stop because it had a ton of straight cayenne on it.

I waited for 5 minutes and went to find a manager, I spoke with another waitress who said she was on break and would come see me shortly and took the wings for a second time.

Our waitress came back apologizing again, and I reiterated my food allergies and that this was serious. She promised to make sure there was no more problems. She delivered the wings shortly after and the 3rd time, no spice, just incredibly over cooked. I assume the chef wasn't happy.

I hadn't received my main dish at this point while the others had been out for awhile. When it came, it was covered in peppers and appeared to have chili flake as well. The table tried it and reported it was spicy. At this point people were finishing up their meals and I was very embarrassed.  The group insisted on waiting until I had my dinner and ended up sitting there for 30 minutes until my food came and I finished it as fast as I could.

This whole experience was very embarrassing and is simply inexcusable.

P.S. The manager never came to talk to me.<//text>

<userid>107596985540899686706</userid><user_name>Jennifer Lo<//user_name><Time>1511149635362< /Time>< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
After hearing Martin Yan had opened a restaurant and since I had just moved to SF, it was perfect timing. I loved watching Yan Can Cook as a child and I was excited to have the opportunity to see what his restaurant had to offer.

The wild boar scissor cut noodles are a must try. They are so flavorful and have that nice "wok" flavor to them. It can be a bit salty to some palates but it goes well with the entrees. The Beijing knife cut noodles are also worth trying. They are cooked well and are a nice vegetarian option. The beef hand pulled noodles are also good. The presentation is very neat and the broth is quite tasty. But I would recommend trying the dry noodles to the noodle soups are you can taste more of the "wok" flavor and it's much easier to share. Also, the chefs sometimes put on a show as they pull the noodles right in front of your table.

My favorite entree has to be the five spice pork ribs. Don't let the word ribs deceive you into the dish being messy and hard to eat because it's quite the opposite. The meat was so tender and fell right off the bone. The pork ribs I presume is slow cooked and then fried a bit on the outside to give it that crispy golden color and taste. It's so delicious that you must try for yourself. The lamb chops are also on the top of my list. It's seasoned with cumin and chili powder and tastes so flavorful and juicy. Also, you can give the Peking duck a try. It's not the best Peking duck but it is still good and satisfies the craving.

From the small eats, the tea smoked pork belly sliders are wonderful. They are tender and goes nicely with the bun. But I have to say I've had better as the pork belly wasn't melt in your mouth.

I've made three visits here already and have loved the food and experience here each time. It's situated right under the dome at the Westfield and it's a perfect place to grab dinner and a movie. I love this place and of course I'm planning future visits.< /Text>

<rating>4< /rating>< Text>
It's a really nice spot for a mall. Now we have three options at the Westfiled Center for a good meal and ambience. I really like the way the new-asian influence is reflected throughout the decor, with a great open bar, awesome staff and tasty cocktails. Try the MaiTai, it was really well done. We ordered appetizers and they all were super good, perfect setting for happy hour or even a quick meal before going to the movies. Great selection of drinks, food and overall a nice experience. Would come back again.<//Text>

<Text>Yes, it's in the mall but despite that, M.Y. China serves up some pretty tasty Chinese food. They've got the standard kung pao and honey walnut shrimp that are now cornerstones in most American Chinese restaurants but things like their pork dumplings (xiao long bao) and lots of their noodles are definitely on point and delicious. Very extensive menu, nice airy interior. I'd say it's a little bit more upscale too, some of the fish and seafood entrees are pushing $40 but a good meal can definitely be had for less than that.<//Text>< pictures>

111670789696108204659</user>
<review>At this elegant establishment, Chinese cuisine is elevated to a previously unimaginable level. How? It's Martin Yan's place. 'Nuff said. MUST try: wild boar lettuce cups, whole wheat potstickers, slow cooked beef & hand pulled noodles, pork & black truffle dumplings. Make reservations in advance, or risk getting buried in the throng of people waiting for a seat. This addictive restaurant can get hectic and the wait long. Great for groups or dates, though the noise level can become a hinderance to private conversations. Try to get seated at a booth if you can.</review>< pictures>

< rating>

< user_name>
Shawn C< /user_name>
<gmap_id>0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1< /gmap_id><user>100884676252145293797< /user>< text>
I glanced in the kitchen as we were being seated and swore I saw one guy skipping rope while another was snipping a softball with scissors. The things these restaurants do these days to be different.... Turns out this is how they make the noodles. Lots of twirling in the air and snipping noodles from a ball of dough.

We ordered:
crispy springrolls - nothing special here
stir fly baby bok choy - garlic and anchovies brought it alive
honey glazed bbq pork - good but the same thing you'd get in any Chinese place
scissor-cut noodles - I liked the lumpy cut noodles
squid ink snap noodles - my favorite--delicious doughy noodles with scallops and jumbo shrimp mixed in

Plenty of food with one IPA = $67 + tip

With Chinatown a few blocks up, I'm not sure we'll be returning to the mall the next time we have a hankering for some Chinese food. But worth checking out.</text>

<user_id>102347880375756673498< /user_id><Name>Raymond Berkoski<//Name>< time>
1401425047920</time>
<Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
Decided to check this place out after watching a Martin Yan episode on TV and heading to SF the following week. While excellent, I have to say the main course was the most disappointing. I started off with the drink of Tsingtao and a shot of a strong Chinese alcohol (like a Chinese sake or something) which I highly enjoyed. We grabbed dumplings and bao for appetizers which were incredible. For the main course I had Milk Oolong Tea and crispy noodles in XO sauce. While tasty, the sauce was overly sweet (I'd say Americanized) and I was hoping for something a little more authentic. Again, it wasn't bad, but I would order something else next time. For dessert I had the Lychee Penna Cotta which was very unique and much less sweet than the main dish. Overall a very good place.< /text>

<userid>100317833931102218342< /userid><Name>Daivat Dholakia< /Name><date>1399835823550</date><Rate>5<//Rate><text>M.Y. China is a hidden gem in the Westfield mall in Downtown San Francisco. Its one of the restaurants "Under the Dome". Though it is located in a mall, this place has great ambiance (perfect for date night) and the food here is A-M-A-Z-I-N-G! We ordered the crispy tofu, scissor cut noodles with tofu and Kung Pao Tofu! Yes, it is a lot of tofu but we became a fan with the first bit we took of crispy tofu. This was the best tofu my wife and I have had every period. It melts in your mouth yet doesn't break that easily. The crispy tofu was perfectly crisp and nicely spiced. We will be coming here again to try out other dishes, specially the long noodles which are famous here.

Tip: if you like lychee, try the lychee panna cota dessert here, you will regret not trying it!<//text><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None< /response><Gmap_id>0x808580860ca8f4fb:0x170fd44206b9ead1</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
